Offered for the discriminating collector or if you would just like to acquire
a perfect condition vintage Browning firearm in a Same as New and Unfired 
condition is a Browning BDA 380. chambered in .380acp. Manufactured in 1979 
by Beretta for Browning Arms Company who imported and sold the pistols within
the U.S.A.

First produced in 1977 and discontinued in 1997. Resurrected I believe
in 2000 and produced possibly through 2009 with most being in a bright
nickel finish. The newest production years is only a guess and based on
the fact I have owned several with two that had serial number date codes
of 2000 and 2009.

This BDA .380's bright blued finish is virtually flawless and looks as
new as the day it was manufactured. Note the Browning "B" Medallion on
the wood grips which was commonly used up through 1985 and then
discontinued and replaced by the well known "Buckmark" logo. The pistol
comes in the original Styrofoam box with factory outer box and has its
original 13 round magazine along with a factory supplied bore brush (Not
seen in photos and located in a cavity on backside of Styrofoam box) as
well as the owners manual.

title: For Sale:  1848 Allen Thurber & Co Pepperbox 6 Shot .31 All numbers match, fully cycles with accurate hammer drop
postcontent:
My grandparents recently sold their estate and I volunteered to sell their guns. I am starting with the items that do not need a FFL dealer transfer - such as this gun.
I don't think people in NJ can buy an Antique gun w/o a FFL licensed dealer receiving the gun (according to other listinggs I have seen).

About this gun - This is a .31 caliber percussion pepperbox. I was told by someone who reviewed all of the guns (who is a antique gun restoration expert) that this little gun is a great collector's gun - for those who like pepperboxes or antique guns.

It is a six shot gun. The barrel fully rotates and cycles. I took a video showing the timing and the action. Numbers on inner workings, walnut grips, and other identifiying pieces all match (as seen in photos). I have not had it restored. It was lubricated in Eezox and wiped down. It was stored in a box for a long time. My grandfather said it was his wife's father's gun. Most of the guns I have to sell are from her father's gun collection. I've researched these guns and those selling them. It seems most people are trying to buff and make them shine. I'll let the buyer do what they want. The original patina on handle, barrel and trigger still exist. The inner workings look clean. 

It is a fun little gun to show people and definitely unique. I considered buying it myself...but I have my own toys that I was told by my wife...I don't need anymore.

From what I have seen for shipping I would have to do FEDEX or UPS Top Priority mail. So I am assuming $20 for shipping. I am willing to entertain reasonable offers. 

If you want additional pictures and the video...I'd be happy to email. 
Will accept check or money order. Will have to wait for check to clear before I will ship. I'm not business so I don't do returns.
